The Executive Secretary and Chief Executive Officer of the Nigerian Shippers Council (NCS), Barr. Hassan Bello has said the recently signed African Continental Free Trade Agreement (AfCFTA) would increase intra-African trade by $35 billion per year or 52% above the baseline by 2022, if successfully implemented. Bello who made this disclosure at the Journal conference on Maximising Benefits of Intra-African Trade Under AfCFTA Regime in Lagos, said the Agreement would have the consequence of imports from outside the continent decrease by $10bn per year. Bello who was represented by James Chabulatuda, the Operations Officers, Consumer Affairs, of the Council said the agricultural and industrial exports would increase by $4bn and $21bn above the baseline. OVER 5,000 NIGERIAN MEN HAVE  OVERCOME POOR BEDROOM PERFORMANCE SYNDROME DUE TO THIS BRILLIANT DISCOVERY Daily Trust reports that the Agreement, protocols were adopted by Summit in March, 2018 following the deposit of the required 22 ratifications, the Agreement came into effect on 30th May, 2019. Nigeria and Benin signed the Agreement during the July 2019 summit in Muamey, Niger. As at 25th September, 2019, all countries except Eritrea have signed the Agreement. Bello added that the AfCFTA would boost small and medium sized enterprises by 80% in Africaâ€™s growth by using regional markets as stepping stones for expanding into overseas markets outside Africa.  Why Buhari put AU trade deal on hold Why Nigeria trades less within Africa AfCFTA; Better late than never